  "prompt": "Does it hurt to get stitches?",
  "response": "Getting stitches can involve some discomfort, but the level of pain varies depending on the situation. Here\u2019s what to expect:\n\n1. **Numbing the Area**: If the wound requires stitches, the doctor will usually clean the area and administer a local anesthetic to numb it. This injection might feel like a brief pinch or sting, but it reduces pain significantly during the procedure.\n\n2. **During the Stitching**: Once the area is numbed, you may feel some pressure or tugging as the stitches are applied, but it shouldn\u2019t be painful. If you do feel pain, let the healthcare provider know so they can adjust the anesthesia or approach.\n\n3. **After the Procedure**: Once the anesthetic wears off, the area might feel sore or tender for a few days. Over-the-counter pain relievers like acetaminophen or ibuprofen can help manage discomfort.\n\n4. **Healing Process**: As the wound heals, you might experience mild itching or tightness around the stitches, which is normal. Avoid picking or pulling at them to prevent pain or complications.\n\nIf you\u2019re anxious about the process, talk to your healthcare provider\u2014they can help reassure you and make the experience as comfortable as possible.",
